Justification: The P-type arguments collectively establish that Elian has good taste, not bad taste. Specifically, one P argument uses the rule "Elian either lacks refinement or has good taste, but not both" together with the fact that Elian is sophisticated (hence does not lack refinement) to conclude Elian has good taste. Since "Either Elian has good taste or he has bad taste, but not both" is given, good taste directly contradicts bad taste. Therefore, the claim "Elian has bad taste" is false.